{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"851"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/851"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.04,0.06,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/851"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30963"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents with a six hour history of intermittent colicky abdominal pain, nausea and a single episode of vomiting. The pain is worst in her upper abdomen. She has no other symptoms. Her medical history is unremarkble.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 115/80 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.2C. Her abdomen is soft, with no localising signs. A urine dipstick returns negative for blood, nitrites, and leukocytes. A plain abdominal film is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the abnormality seen on the X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric stone","Calcified lymph node","Faecolith of the appendix","Phlebolith","Gallstone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom its situation and appearance, the area of calcification in the right upper quadrant is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstone\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). The diagnosis is made as much from the position as anything else - although such radio-opaque gallstones will often have concentric layers of calcification, which can help in the differentiation from other calcifying processes. The other options listed can all become sufficiently calcified to be visible on a plain radiograph - and in such instances, they would be incidental findings. With regards to the detection of gallstones, due to their cholesterol content, plain X-rays and CT have low sensitivity and the gold standard imaging investigation is either ultrasound or magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis for red blood cells is extremely sensitive for the presence of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric stone\u003C/strong\u003E (due to abrasion of the ureteric wall), especially when symptomatic. A negative urine dipstick would be extremely unlikely in this setting. The abnormality\u0027s location would be highly atypical for a \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ephlebolith\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcified lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the finding of the (calcified) gallstone is probably incidental, as the patient\u0027s symptoms and signs are not characteristic of either biliary colic or cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radio-opaque gallstones will often have concentric layers of calcification.","Due to their cholesterol content, the gold standard imaging investigation for gallstones is either ultrasound or MRCP."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK, et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdominal Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019.","https://radiopaedia.org/articles/gallstones-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19687"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19688"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19687"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/68f0a9d0-626a-4071-ac59-a2841864c6ce.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/68f0a9d0-626a-4071-ac59-a2841864c6ce.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":383,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19688"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e78cea3e-9431-4e9d-9b42-3c448d6d74f5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e78cea3e-9431-4e9d-9b42-3c448d6d74f5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":396,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T16:34:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T16:34:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"851"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T